	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Sep 17th 10:05 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2507><span id=Scholar>Tomlin</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>301 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.88]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Here's my take on things:<br><br>These disciplines do not make player characters invulnerable, they simply guarantee your successfull skill check for riposte, dodge, parry, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;For example, a necromancer using Harmshield is invulnerable.  If you cast a direct damage spell on them, they will not take damage because they are invulnerable.  On the other hand, if you cast a direct damage spell on a warrior using their riposte discipline, it can still do damage to them, since they can't riposte against a spell.<br><br>Also, the damage absorption effects should not count as invulnerability.  Against invulnerable characters, any incoming damage simply doesn't happen; against characters with damage absorption effects, the incoming damage is still applied, only it gets applied to the damage absorption effect instead of the character, eventually "using up" the effect.</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
